# Three-Act Structure
= (The foundational structure of modern Western filmmaking.) Goal: To establish a clear, directional progression of conflict from stability to chaos, and back to new stability.

## Exposition/Status Quo
= Introduce the protagonist in their normal world. Establish their flaws and what they think they want.

## Inciting Incident (The Catalyst)
= An event occurs that shatters the status quo and presents a problem the hero cannot ignore. This forces them to act.

## Plot Point 1 / Break into Act II
= The protagonist makes the decision—the point of no return. They commit fully to the adventure, leaving their old life behind.

## Rising Action
= A series of escalating challenges and setbacks. Stakes increase with every scene.

## Midpoint
= The point of maximum false victory or catastrophic failure. Something major shifts, raising the stakes further. Often a dramatic reversal that forces a change in tactics.

## Rising Tension/Complication
= Obstacles become personal and desperate. Allies are lost; enemies grow stronger. The protagonist realizes they cannot solve the problem with their current skills.

## Plot Point 2 / Crisis
= The deepest despair point (often called "All Is Lost"). All hope seems extinguished, forcing a moment of emotional reckoning for the character.

## Climax
= The ultimate showdown. The protagonist must use all they have learned about themselves and their world to solve the central conflict permanently. This is the peak tension moment.

## Falling Action
= The immediate aftermath of the climax. Loose ends are addressed; the emotional dust settles.

## Resolution (The New Normal)
= Show the protagonist in their transformed life, having solved the problem and found a stable equilibrium.
